node selectors:
to avoid resource waste, we label nodes 'Large', 'Small' etc. making sure that the proper size of pod will be scheduled into the right node.
set node size in pod definition file:
spec.nodeSelector.size

then:
$ k create -f pod-definition.yaml

to set the size of a node, run
$ k label nodes <node-name> <label-key>=<label-value>
eg. k label nodes node01 size=Large

but if we need to set Large or Medium, or Not Small these complicated values, we need to use node affinity


node affinity:
in pod definition file:
spec:
  affinity:
    nodeAffinity:
      requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:    //means that even though the node size is changed, the pod would ignore it and keep running on it
        nodeSelectorTerms:
        - matchExpressions:
          - key: disktype          //or size
            operator: In                            //making sure the pod would be put on a node which has spec defined in this nodeAffinity section
            values:
            - ssd                  //or Large


difference of taints and tolerance and node affinity:
if only apply taints and tolerance, the pod would be put into a node which doesnt have any taints and tolerance;
if only apply node affinity, an undesired pod would be put in a node which has a matching pod already.
